<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="439" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1368,1897]" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1836,1861]" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fang &amp; Xing" authorityYear="2018" box="[908,998,1836,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Longicornus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="439" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis box="[908,998,1836,1860]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="439">furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, referring to the aedeagal shaft with a pair of furcate processes.
</paragraph>
